Running a business as a freelance creative introvert who is very attached to their private life shouldn't be complicated, and yet it often is. The majority of online resources and coaches tell you to work with large (and diabolical) technology companies using extrovert techniques. Make ads here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service checked, be available 24/7, answer questions with a video of yourself, answer right away. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
This is a year of transition for me.
I don't want to fuel the large technology companies with my money, data, and energy. Nor do I want coaches who have a single extrovert solution that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activity while fighting the idea that I've long believed in, that you have to do things in a certain way to succeed.
Wish me good luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I have left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I have also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to an EU-based CRM for better GDPR compliance, and I will transfer my activity over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully benefiting from SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
